      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The memory leak is a sneaky one, isn't it? A classic case of a \"goblin in the attic\" - you can't quite see it, but it's definitely there. To track down the leak systematically, I'd recommend using a combination of manual debugging techniques and some clever C++ idioms.\n\nFirst, let's start by modifying your `process_sensor_data` function to print out the memory addresses of the objects it creates. This will give you a rough idea of where the memory is being allocated:\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet->status == VALID) {\n        DataLog* log = new DataLog(packet->payload);\n        log_store->push_back(log);\n        std::cout << \"Allocated memory address: \" << log << std::endl;\n        \n        if (log_store->size() > MAX_LOG_SIZE) {\n            log_store->remove_oldest(); \n        }\n    }\n}\n```\nThis will print out the memory addresses of the `DataLog` objects as they're created. Look for any addresses that seem to be stuck in the `log_store` vector - those might be the culprits.\n\nNext, let's try",
