      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In that case, we can try to use some more lightweight techniques to monitor the heap usage. One approach is to use a custom allocator that keeps track of the objects it allocates and frees. We can create a wrapper around the standard allocator that logs the allocations and deallocations.\n\nHere's an example of how you could implement a custom allocator that logs the allocations and deallocations:\n```cpp\nclass LoggingAllocator : public std::allocator<DataLog*> {\npublic:\n    LoggingAllocator() : alloc_(new std::allocator<DataLog*>()) {}\n\n    void* allocate(std::size_t n, std::allocator<void>* alloc) {\n        void* ptr = alloc_->allocate(n, sizeof(DataLog));\n        if (ptr) {\n            log_ += n;\n        }\n        return ptr;\n    }\n\n    void deallocate(void* p, std::size_t n) {\n        log_ -= n;\n        delete[] p;\n    }\n\nprivate:\n    std::allocator<DataLog*>* alloc_;\n    std::size_t log_;\n};\n```\nWe can then use this custom allocator in our `process_sensor_data` function:\n```cpp\nLoggingAllocator log_allocator;\n\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if",
