    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"goblin in the attic\" analogy is a good one, isn't it? In C++, these kinds of \"hidden\" leaks often hide in the shadows, and it's not always a simple matter of just missing a `delete`.\n\nOne common pattern is the use of smart pointers, but not in the way you might think. Sometimes, smart pointers can actually introduce memory leaks if they're not used correctly. For example, if you have a `std::unique_ptr` that's supposed to own a dynamically allocated object, but the object is never deleted, the `unique_ptr` will keep the object alive indefinitely.\n\nAnother pattern is the use of raw pointers and manual memory management. If you're using raw pointers and manually managing memory with `new` and `delete`, it's easy to forget to delete objects, especially if they're not immediately used.\n\nBut sometimes, the leaks can be more complex. For example, if you're using a third-party library that has a memory leak, or if you're using a custom allocator that's not properly implemented, it can be difficult to track down the source of the leak.\n\nIn your case, the fact that the leak only shows up after 4-5 hours of steady state operation",
